Part I - Exploratory Data Analysis¶

by Alberto Ivo Vieira¶

Introduction¶

The dataset used for this analysis is the Ford GoBike System Data, which contains information about bike-sharing trips in the San Francisco Bay Area. The dataset includes various features such as trip duration, start and end times, user type (Subscriber or Customer), and geographic information (e.g., start and end station locations). The analysis focuses on understanding how trip duration varies by age group, user type, and other demographic factors. Key insights will be drawn from visualizations and statistical summaries to inform potential improvements in the bike-sharing service.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

Based on the observations above, the dataset columns are int, float or object, but any of them should be datetime or categorical. There are only 197 missing values in the dataset, which is not a lot considering the dataset has 183412 entries. The dataset has 16 columns and 183412 rows. The mean age of the users is 40 years old, with a minimum age of 24 and a maximum age of 147 (Definitelly error) years old. The mean trip duration is about 12 minutes, with a minimum duration of 61 seconds and a maximum duration of 1424 minutes.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest in this dataset are the age of the users and the duration of the trips. I want to investigate if there is a correlation between the age of the users and the duration of their trips. I also want to investigate if there are any differences in the trip durations between different user types (customers and subscribers) and if the age of the users has any impact on the user type.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features that will help support my investigation are the age, duration, and user_type columns. The age column will provide information about the users' ages, the duration column will provide information about the trip durations, and the user_type column will provide information about the type of user (customer or subscriber). PS: I will create the age column from the member_birth_year column. And I will create the duration column from the duration_sec column.

In [44]:
df_clean['age'] = (current_year - df_raw['member_birth_year']).astype('Int32') # create age column
df_clean['duration'] = df_raw['duration_sec'] / 60  # convert duration from seconds to minutes
df_clean['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df_raw['start_time']) # convert start_time to datetime
df_clean['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df_raw['end_time']) # convert end_time to datetime
df_clean['user_type'] = df_raw['user_type'].astype('category') # convert user_type to categorical
df_clean['member_gender'] = df_raw['member_gender'].astype('category') # convert member_gender to categorical
df_clean['member_birth_year'] = df_raw['member_birth_year'].astype('Int32') # convert to Int32

I've removed all age above 100 years old from the dataset, as they are likely to be data entry errors or users entering incorrect birth years. We can also see that the majority of users are between 20 and 60 years old, with a median age of around 35 years old.

Based on the "Distribution of User Ages" graph and the context of the code, I can explain what it shows us:¶

  • Normal Distribution with Skewness: The age distribution has an approximately normal shape, but with a slight skew to the right (longer tail for older ages).

  • Main Concentration: Most users are concentrated between the ages of 25 and 45, with the peak of the distribution occurring around the ages of 30-35.

  • Main Peak: There is a clear concentration of young adult users, indicating that the Ford GoBike service is most popular among people in their 30s.

  • Right Tail: There is a gradual decrease in the number of users as age increases, but there is still a significant presence of users up to the ages of 60-70.

  • Effective Data Cleaning: Because you filtered ages between 10 and 90 (df_clean = df_clean[(df_clean['age'] >= 10) & (df_clean['age'] <= 90)]), the graph shows a more realistic distribution, without the extreme outliers that were previously identified (such as ages over 100).

  • Service Demographics: The pattern suggests that bike-sharing is primarily used by young professionals and adults, possibly for urban commuting, such as work and leisure.

  • The KDE curve (smooth line) confirms this distribution and helps better visualize the central tendency of the data.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Yes, I performed some data cleaning and transformations to tidy up the dataset. Specifically, I created new columns for age and duration to make the analysis more straightforward. I also converted the start_time and end_time columns to datetime format for better handling of time-related data. Additionally, I converted the user_type and member_gender columns to categorical data types to optimize memory usage and improve performance during analysis.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Yes, I noticed that the distribution of trip durations was highly skewed, with a significant number of short trips and a few extremely long trips. But, in this case, I can't tell for sure if these long trips are outliers or if they represent legitimate usage patterns. Therefore, I decided not to remove them but to keep them in the analysis. However, I did filter the ages to be between 10 and 90 years old to remove any unrealistic values that could skew the analysis. This was done to ensure that the age data was more accurate and representative of the actual user base.

  • Age-Independent User Type Distribution: The "Distribution of User Type by Age Group" shows that across all age groups, the proportion of Subscribers vs. Customers remains relatively consistent, indicating that subscription preference is not strongly influenced by age demographics.

In the "Trip Duration by Age Group and User Type" graph, we can see that Subscribers consistently have shorter trip durations across all age groups compared to Customers. This suggests that Subscribers are likely using the service for regular, short-distance commuting, while Customers may be taking longer, more leisurely rides. Additionally, the trend of increasing trip duration with age is more pronounced among Customers, indicating that older users in this group may be using the service for recreational purposes rather than quick commutes.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at my features of interest (age and trip duration) were the user_type and member_gender columns. By analyzing trip duration across different age groups while also considering user type, I was able to uncover distinct usage patterns between Subscribers and Customers. Subscribers tended to have shorter trip durations, likely due to regular commuting needs, while Customers had longer trips, possibly for leisure. Additionally, examining trip duration by gender revealed that female users, particularly in the Subscriber category, had shorter trips compared to their male counterparts.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

One surprising interaction was the significant increase in trip duration for older Customers, suggesting that this group may be using the service for more leisurely purposes. In contrast, younger Subscribers maintained consistently short trip durations, highlighting the different ways these groups utilize the service.

Conclusions¶

Summary of Main Findings¶

Through this comprehensive data exploration of the Ford GoBike dataset (February 2019), several key insights emerged:

Dataset Characteristics:¶

  • Dataset Size: 183,412 trips with 16 variables, after cleaning 175,068 valid records
  • Data Quality: Successfully handled missing values and extreme outliers (ages >90 years)
  • Time Period: February 2019 Ford GoBike trip data from San Francisco Bay Area

Key Findings:¶

User Demographics:¶
  • Age Distribution: Users are primarily young to middle-aged adults (25-45 years), with peak around 30-35 years
  • User Types: Subscribers dramatically outnumber Customers (~85% vs ~15%), indicating strong subscription model success
  • Age-Independent Subscription: Subscription preference remains consistent across all age groups
Trip Patterns:¶
  • Duration Distribution: Highly right-skewed with most trips lasting 5-15 minutes, typical of urban commuting
  • Usage Purpose: Short trip durations suggest primary use for last-mile transportation and daily commuting
  • Efficient Utilization: Quick turnover supports high bike fleet efficiency
Relationships Between Variables:¶
  • Age vs Duration: Moderate positive correlation - older users tend to take slightly longer trips
  • User Type Consistency: Subscription dominance is maintained across all age demographics
  • Commuting Focus: Pattern suggests service optimized for working professionals' transportation needs

Data Exploration Process Reflection:¶

Steps Taken:¶
  1. Data Loading & Initial Assessment: Examined structure, data types, and missing values
  2. Data Cleaning: Created age variable, converted durations to minutes, handled outliers
  3. Univariate Analysis: Explored individual variable distributions with histograms and count plots
  4. Bivariate Analysis: Investigated relationships using scatter plots, box plots, and grouped visualizations
  5. Multivariate Analysis: Used faceted plots and correlation analysis to understand complex relationships
Methodological Strengths:¶
  • Systematic Approach: Followed Question-Visualization-Observations framework throughout
  • Appropriate Visualizations: Used histograms for continuous variables, count plots for categorical data
  • Data Quality Focus: Carefully handled outliers and missing data to ensure reliable analysis
  • Multiple Perspectives: Examined data from univariate, bivariate, and multivariate viewpoints
Key Insights for Business:¶
  • Strong subscription model validation across all demographics
  • Service effectively serves its intended purpose (short urban trips)
  • Primary user base is working-age professionals
  • High efficiency and utilization patterns support business sustainability

The analysis confirms that Ford GoBike has successfully established itself as a commuter-focused bike-sharing service with a strong subscription base and efficient usage patterns ideal for urban transportation needs.
